[49m[38;5;10m+    105[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    106[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The AWS Implementation
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    107[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    108[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The AWS implementation is shaped by the streaming nature of the workload. Continuous monitor data lands in a stream, gets processed in near real time, and triggers alerts within seconds to a couple of minutes. The architecture below is a streaming-first design that also handles intermittent flowsheet data through the same pipeline.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    109[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    110[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Why These Services
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    111[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    112[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Kinesis Data Streams for vital sign ingestion.** Bedside monitor feeds are continuous and high-volume by hospital standards (a few hundred records per second for a 500-bed hospital). [Kinesis Data Streams](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/streams/latest/dev/introduction.html) is built for this shape of data: durable, ordered, replayable, and integrates natively with the downstream Lambda and Managed Flink consumers. The HL7 ORU messages from device gateways or interface engines (Mirth, Rhapsody, Cloverleaf) get translated to canonical JSON records and pushed to Kinesis as the system of intake.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    113[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    114[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Managed Service for Apache Flink for streaming processing.** The artifact filter, the per-patient baseline state, the multi-parameter scoring, and the trajectory detection all run as a [Managed Flink](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/managed-flink/latest/java/what-is.html) application. Flink is the right tool because it natively supports keyed state per patient (so each patient's baseline and detector state lives in one logical place), event-time processing with watermarks (so the system handles late-arriving and out-of-order data correctly), and window operations (so sliding-window slope detection and EWMA computations are first-class operations). The alternative of doing everything in Lambda is workable for low-volume floor monitoring but breaks down for continuous monitoring at hospital scale.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    115[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    116[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon Timestream for time-series storage.** Vital sign records and computed scores both have time-series shape (patient as dimension, timestamp as time, value as measure) and are queried as time series (recent N hours of data for a patient). [Timestream](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/timestream/latest/developerguide/what-is-timestream.html) is purpose-built for this access pattern with automatic tiering between memory and magnetic storage, native time-series query functions, and significantly better cost and performance than relational databases for this workload.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    117[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    118[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon DynamoDB for patient state and surfaced alerts.** The current per-patient baseline, the most recent score, and the active surfaced alerts all live in DynamoDB. The access pattern is single-patient lookup at low latency, which is exactly DynamoDB's wheelhouse. DynamoDB also serves the EHR-integration layer (CDS Hooks) at single-digit-millisecond latency.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    119[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    120[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS Lambda for clinical relevance scoring and alert delivery.** The relevance rule layer is conditional logic with lookups against patient context (current medications, recent interventions, unit type). Lambda is the right fit: low-latency, stateless except for the read-side lookups, easy to update rules without redeploying the streaming application.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    121[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    122[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SageMaker for joint deterioration models.** Production systems typically run NEWS2 in the streaming pipeline as the primary score, with a more sophisticated joint model (eCART-like, Epic-DI-like, or a custom model) running alongside as a "second opinion." That model is hosted on a SageMaker real-time endpoint, called from the Flink application or from Lambda after each new measurement. SageMaker Pipelines handles training and retraining with versioned model artifacts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    123[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    124[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon S3 for raw data, model artifacts, and analytics.** Raw HL7 messages and translated JSON records land in S3 partitioned by date and unit. Model training data, baseline configurations, and clinical rule definitions live in S3 with versioning enabled. The historical record is the input for retraining and for retrospective alert tuning.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    125[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    126[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon SNS / Amazon Pinpoint for clinical paging.** Surfaced alerts that need to reach the rapid response team or charge nurse pager flow through SNS to the appropriate notification channel (pager gateway, push notification, SMS to assigned phones). Amazon Pinpoint can layer on for richer in-app notifications.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    127[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    128[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon EventBridge for orchestration of non-streaming work.** Periodic baseline recalibration jobs, model retraining triggers, and alert suppression rule reloads run on EventBridge schedules.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    129[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    130[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **AWS HealthLake for the FHIR view (optional).** When the hospital's broader analytics stack uses HealthLake as the FHIR datastore, vital signs flow into it as FHIR Observation resources. This is not required for the streaming alert pipeline (Timestream is the operational store), but it is the right home for the historical record when integrated into a broader FHIR-native architecture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    131[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    132[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Amazon CloudWatch for monitoring.** Pipeline health, end-to-end latency from measurement to alert, alert volume per unit, alert acceptance rate by clinicians, and baseline drift all flow to CloudWatch with alarms on degradation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    133[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    134[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Architecture Diagram
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    135[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    136[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```mermaid
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    137[0m:[38;5;10m[49m flowchart LR
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    138[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     A[Bedside Monitors<br/>Philips / GE / Mindray] -->|HL7 ORU| B[Interface Engine<br/>Mirth / Rhapsody]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    139[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     AA[EHR Flowsheets<br/>FHIR Observation] --> B
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    140[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     AB[Wearables / Remote<br/>Monitoring] --> B
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    141[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     B -->|Translated JSON| C[Kinesis Data Streams<br/>vital-signs-stream]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    142[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Stream| D[Managed Flink<br/>artifact filter +<br/>baseline + NEWS2 +<br/>trajectory detector]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    143[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     C -->|Raw archive| E[S3 Bucket<br/>raw-vitals/]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    144[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D -->|Vital sign + score| F[Amazon Timestream<br/>vitals-and-scores]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    145[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D -->|Patient state| G[DynamoDB<br/>patient-state]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    146[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D -->|Trajectory event| H[Lambda<br/>clinical relevance]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    147[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     H -->|Context lookup| G
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    148[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     H -->|Joint score| I[SageMaker Endpoint<br/>deterioration model]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    149[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     H -->|Surfaced alert| J[DynamoDB<br/>active-alerts]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    150[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     H -->|Page| K[SNS / Pinpoint<br/>RRT pager / Nurse phone]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    151[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     J -->|Query| L[EHR CDS Hooks /<br/>Charge Nurse Dashboard]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    152[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     M[EventBridge Schedule<br/>nightly] -->|Trigger| N[Step Functions<br/>baseline recal +<br/>rule reload]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    153[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     D -->|Errors / metrics| O[CloudWatch<br/>Alarms + SNS]
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    154[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    155[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style D fill:#9f9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    156[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style I fill:#ff9,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    157[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     style J fill:#9ff,stroke:#333
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    158[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    159[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    160[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Prerequisites
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    161[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    162[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Requirement | Details |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    163[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |-------------|---------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    164[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Services** | Amazon Kinesis Data Streams, Amazon Managed Service for Apache Flink, Amazon Timestream, Amazon DynamoDB, AWS Lambda, Amazon SageMaker, Amazon S3, Amazon SNS, Amazon EventBridge, AWS Step Functions, Amazon CloudWatch, AWS KMS |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    165[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **IAM Permissions** | `kinesis:PutRecord`, `kinesis:GetRecords`, `kinesisanalytics:StartApplication`, `timestream:WriteRecords`, `timestream:Select`, `dynamodb:PutItem`, `dynamodb:GetItem`, `dynamodb:Query`, `lambda:InvokeFunction`, `sagemaker:InvokeEndpoint`, `s3:GetObject`, `s3:PutObject`, `sns:Publish`, `kms:Decrypt`, `kms:Encrypt`, `events:PutEvents`, `states:StartExecution` |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    166[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **BAA** | AWS BAA signed. Vital signs are PHI when associated with a patient identifier; every storage and compute service in this pipeline must be on the [HIPAA eligible services](https://aws.amazon.com/compliance/hipaa-eligible-services-reference/) list. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    167[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Encryption** | Kinesis: server-side encryption with customer-managed KMS keys. Timestream: encryption at rest with KMS. DynamoDB: encryption at rest enabled. S3: SSE-KMS with customer-managed CMKs. SageMaker training and inference: encrypted EBS volumes and KMS-encrypted output. CloudWatch log groups: explicit KMS encryption. TLS 1.2 minimum in transit. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    168[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **VPC** | Production: Managed Flink, SageMaker, and Lambda in private subnets with VPC endpoints for Kinesis, Timestream, DynamoDB, S3, KMS, and CloudWatch Logs. Required posture for HIPAA workloads with PHI. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    169[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **CloudTrail** | Enabled across all data-plane services. Vital sign data and the alerts derived from it are sensitive PHI; the audit trail of who accessed which patient's trajectory is non-negotiable. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    170[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Sample Data** | Synthetic vital sign streams for development. The [PhysioNet/MIMIC-IV](https://physionet.org/content/mimiciv/) and [eICU Collaborative Research Database](https://physionet.org/content/eicu-crd/) projects publish de-identified ICU and ward data including continuous vital signs (credentialed access required). The [Synthea](https://github.com/synthetichealth/synthea) project generates synthetic FHIR Observation resources including vitals. Never use real PHI in dev. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    171[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Cost Estimate** | Kinesis Data Streams: ~$50–$200/month per shard depending on volume. Managed Flink: ~$300–$1,200/month for a small-to-medium application. Timestream: ~$100–$500/month for ingest and query at hospital scale. DynamoDB: ~$50–$200/month. SageMaker inference (small endpoint, used selectively): ~$100/month. Lambda, S3, SNS, EventBridge, Step Functions: ~$100/month combined. Total: ~$800–$3,500/month per hospital depending on bed count, monitoring density, and feature scope. |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    172[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    173[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): V1. Verify Kinesis, Managed Flink, Timestream, and SageMaker pricing assumptions reflect current AWS rates. Pricing changes; confirm against the AWS pricing calculator before publication. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    174[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    175[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Ingredients
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    176[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    177[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | AWS Service | Role |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    178[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |------------|------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    179[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Kinesis Data Streams** | Durable, ordered ingestion of vital sign records from bedside monitors, EHR flowsheets, and wearables |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    180[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Managed Service for Apache Flink** | Streaming processor running artifact filtering, per-patient baseline state, NEWS2 scoring, and trajectory detection (sliding-window slope, EWMA, CUSUM) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    181[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon Timestream** | Time-series database for vital sign history and computed scores; serves the longitudinal queries needed by the trajectory detector and the dashboards |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    182[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon DynamoDB** | Per-patient current state (latest score, baseline, active flags) and the surfaced alert table consumed by EHR CDS Hooks and dashboards |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    183[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Lambda** | Clinical relevance rule engine; alert composition; CDS Hooks responder; suppression and routing logic |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    184[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SageMaker** | Hosts the optional joint deterioration model (eCART-like or custom) used as a second opinion alongside NEWS2; offline retraining runs on SageMaker Pipelines |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    185[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon S3** | Raw vital sign archive, model artifacts, baseline configurations, clinical rule definitions, and historical analytics |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    186[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon SNS / Amazon Pinpoint** | Clinical paging to rapid response team, charge nurses, and on-call providers |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    187[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS Step Functions** | Orchestrates non-streaming workflows: nightly baseline recalibration, model retraining triggers, rule reloads |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    188[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon EventBridge** | Schedules the periodic non-streaming workflows |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    189[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **AWS KMS** | Customer-managed CMKs for encryption across Kinesis, Timestream, DynamoDB, S3, and SageMaker |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    190[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | **Amazon CloudWatch** | Logs, metrics, alarms for pipeline health, end-to-end latency, alert volume per unit, and baseline drift |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    191[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
