[49m[38;5;10m+    533[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ### Expected Results
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    534[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    535[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Sample surfaced alert payload for a deteriorating med-surg patient:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    536[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    537[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```json
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    538[0m:[38;5;10m[49m {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    539[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "patient_id": "patient-9b3a4c87",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    540[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "alert_id": "alert-d4f6e1c2-9a87-4b22-9f01-8a7c3b9d4e21",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    541[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "alert_ts": "2026-04-18T03:32:14Z",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    542[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "severity": "high",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    543[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "news2_score": 8,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    544[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "score_components": {
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    545[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "respiratory_rate": 3,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    546[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "oxygen_saturation": 2,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    547[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "supplemental_oxygen": 0,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    548[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "temperature": 1,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    549[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "systolic_bp": 1,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    550[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "heart_rate": 1,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    551[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     "consciousness": 0
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    552[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   },
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    553[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "score_trajectory": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    554[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"ts": "2026-04-18T02:30:00Z", "score": 2},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    555[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"ts": "2026-04-18T02:45:00Z", "score": 3},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    556[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"ts": "2026-04-18T03:00:00Z", "score": 4},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    557[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"ts": "2026-04-18T03:15:00Z", "score": 6},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    558[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"ts": "2026-04-18T03:30:00Z", "score": 8}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    559[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    560[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "elevated_duration_minutes": 47,
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    561[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "triggering_signals": [
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    562[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"signal": "respiratory_rate", "current_value": 26, "baseline_24h": 17, "deviation": 9},
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    563[0m:[38;5;10m[49m     {"signal": "oxygen_saturation", "current_value": 91, "baseline_24h": 96, "deviation": -5}
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    564[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   ],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    565[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "patient_location": "5West bed 412",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    566[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "routing_targets": ["rrt_pager", "charge_nurse", "ehr_di_column"],
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    567[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "explanation_text": "NEWS2 score has risen from 2 to 8 over the last hour. Respiratory rate elevated to 26 (baseline 17 over 24h). Oxygen saturation dropped to 91% (baseline 96%). Heart rate trending upward. Pattern is consistent with developing infection or respiratory compromise. Recommend bedside evaluation and consider sepsis workup.",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    568[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "recommended_action": "rapid_response_evaluation",
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    569[0m:[38;5;10m[49m   "model_version": "news2-v2-cusum-v3"
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    570[0m:[38;5;10m[49m }
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    571[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ```
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    572[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    573[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Performance benchmarks:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    574[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    575[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Metric | Typical Value |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    576[0m:[38;5;10m[49m |--------|---------------|
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    577[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | End-to-end latency from measurement to alert (continuous monitoring) | 30 to 90 seconds |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    578[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | End-to-end latency from measurement to alert (intermittent flowsheet) | 5 to 15 minutes |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    579[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Surfaced alerts per nursing unit per shift (after tuning) | 3 to 8 |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    580[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Suppressed-but-detected trajectories per unit per shift | 30 to 80 |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    581[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Lead time vs. clinician-recognized deterioration | 30 minutes to 4 hours (highly patient-dependent) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    582[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Alert acceptance rate (clinician acts on the alert) | 60 to 80 percent (target) |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    583[0m:[38;5;10m[49m | Cost per hospital per month | $800 to $3,500 |
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    584[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    585[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO (TechWriter): A1. Performance benchmarks above are typical figures for production trajectory monitoring systems on med-surg and step-down units. Confirm against published outcomes literature and your reference deployments before publication. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    586[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    587[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Where it struggles:** Patients in the first few hours of admission (the baseline cannot yet be established from in-hospital data). Patients on continuous rate-control medications (beta-blockers blunt the heart rate signal that drives much of NEWS2). Patients with chronic respiratory disease whose baseline saturation is in the high 80s (the threshold-based scoring incorrectly flags their normal state). Pediatric patients (NEWS2 is calibrated for adults; pediatric early warning scores like PEWS need a different scoring layer). Patients with arrhythmias whose heart rate signal is intrinsically noisy (CUSUM trips on the noise). Sustained device artifact during patient activity (ambulation, toileting, repositioning) when the artifact filter doesn't fully suppress it. Multi-bed acute events (when the same trigger affects several patients simultaneously, the surge of alerts can overwhelm the unit even if each is individually accurate).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    588[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    589[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    590[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    591[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Why This Isn't Production-Ready
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    592[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    593[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pseudocode and architecture above demonstrate the pattern. A real deployment requires addressing several gaps that are intentionally outside the scope of a cookbook recipe.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    594[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    595[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Pediatric and population-specific scoring layers.** NEWS2 is calibrated for adults. Hospitals serving pediatric, obstetric, or geriatric populations need population-specific scoring (PEWS for pediatric, Maternal Early Warning Trigger for obstetric, etc.). The trajectory detection layer reuses across populations; the scoring layer does not. Production systems typically run multiple parallel scoring layers and route each patient to the appropriate one based on encounter type, age, and care unit.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    596[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    597[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Medication and intervention awareness.** A patient whose heart rate is rising because they just received atropine is on an expected trajectory. A patient whose blood pressure is dropping because they just received a vasodilator is also expected. The clinical relevance layer in step 6 outlines this conceptually; production systems integrate live medication administration records (MAR) and intervention timestamps to suppress expected trajectories. This is the single biggest reduction in false alarms after the basic pipeline works.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    598[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    599[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Lab and clinical context integration.** The richest deterioration models combine vital sign trajectories with lab values (lactate, white blood cell count, creatinine), clinical assessments (mental status changes documented in nursing notes), and intervention history. Recipe 3.7 (Patient Deterioration Early Warning) covers the multi-modal version of this problem. The vital-sign-only pipeline described here is a useful building block, but the full system integrates the additional signals.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    600[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    601[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Continuous bedside artifact analysis.** The artifact filter described in step 2 handles the obvious cases. Subtle artifact (a slowly drifting SpO2 sensor, an arterial line that has partially clotted off, an ECG with intermittent baseline drift) is harder. Production systems often add a continuous waveform-quality monitoring service that runs alongside the trajectory pipeline and feeds quality information back into the artifact filter.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    602[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    603[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Clinical workflow integration.** A surfaced alert needs to land in the right surface for the unit's workflow. Some units have a central monitoring tech who triages alerts and pages the floor; some have direct-to-pager paths for the rapid response team; some integrate with bed-management dashboards. A pipeline that produces a JSON alert and stops there has not finished the job. The integration with the existing workflow is highly hospital-specific and is typically the longest engineering effort after the math is done.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    604[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    605[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Closed-loop feedback capture.** Every surfaced alert should have a feedback path: did the rapid response team activate? Did the patient transfer to a higher level of care within N hours? Was the alert dismissed as a false alarm? Without feedback capture, the system stays calibrated to its launch-day rules forever. Production systems integrate the alert outcome into a closed-loop tuning pipeline that continuously updates suppression rules and threshold calibrations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    606[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    607[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FDA / SaMD considerations.** A trajectory monitoring system that surfaces alerts to clinical staff sits in a gray zone of FDA software-as-a-medical-device regulation. A system that says "patient is deteriorating; consider sepsis workup" can usually be characterized as clinical decision support and is exempt from premarket review under the 21st Century Cures Act if it meets transparency requirements. A system that says "diagnose sepsis" is not exempt. Working with regulatory counsel on the framing of the surfaced output is non-negotiable for any deployment beyond a research pilot. NEWS2 itself is established practice; the more sophisticated joint models layered on top can shift the regulatory posture.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    608[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    609[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Unit-level and hospital-level surge handling.** When several patients on the same unit deteriorate simultaneously (a respiratory virus surge, a multi-casualty event), the alert pipeline can produce a flood of accurate alerts that overwhelms the unit's response capacity. Production systems include surge-mode logic that consolidates alerts at the unit level, prioritizes by severity, and escalates to incident command rather than overwhelming the front-line nurses.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    610[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    611[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Idempotency and replay safety.** Streaming pipelines can fail and need to recover gracefully. Each step needs to be safe under replay: artifact filtering is deterministic; baseline computation is deterministic given the input; scoring is deterministic; trajectory detection is deterministic. Surfaced alerts need to be deduplicated by alert ID so a replay does not page the rapid response team twice for the same event.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    612[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    613[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-unit baseline transfer.** When a patient transfers from the ED to the floor, or from the floor to the ICU, their baseline state should transfer with them rather than restart. Production systems either persist the baseline state at the patient level (not the encounter level) or have explicit transfer-time logic that hands off the state. Without this, every transfer produces a 4-hour blackout window during which trajectory detection cannot fire.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    614[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    615[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    616[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    617[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Honest Take
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    618[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    619[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The streaming math is the easy part. I have implemented or audited four trajectory monitoring systems across academic, community, and integrated-delivery-network settings, and the streaming detector itself has never been the binding constraint. NEWS2 plus a sliding-window slope plus a CUSUM gets you something like 75% of the available value for 10% of the engineering effort. The remaining 25% comes from the hard, slow, unrewarding work of artifact filtering, baseline tuning, clinical relevance calibration, and workflow integration. Each of those is harder than it looks and each will burn more weeks of your team's calendar than the streaming pipeline did.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    620[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    621[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing that surprised me the first time I built one was how much the clinical leadership does not want a more accurate model. They want a more trustworthy model. Trustworthiness comes from explainability and from low false-alarm rates. NEWS2 wins on both. A black-box deep learning model that beats NEWS2 on AUC by three points but produces alerts the medical director cannot interrogate will lose every adoption fight to NEWS2. The most successful deployments I have seen treat NEWS2 (or whatever the institution's chosen score is) as the public face of the system and use the more sophisticated joint model as a quiet second-opinion check that is invisible to the clinical staff. The second-opinion model raises sensitivity at the margin without breaking the explainability of the primary alert.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    622[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    623[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Alert fatigue is the failure mode and it is structural. The math can be perfect; if your pipeline produces 30 surfaced alerts per nurse per shift, the system will be ignored within a quarter. The clinical relevance layer is not optional and it is not a weekend project. Plan for two months of clinical-leadership conversations, threshold-tuning iterations, suppression-rule tweaks, and shadow-mode running before the system goes live. Plan for the same volume of work after launch on an indefinite basis. The systems that get this right have a dedicated quality team that reviews the alerts weekly and tunes the rules; the systems that don't have a system that gets unplugged.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    624[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    625[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing I would do differently if I were starting over is to spend the first three months running the pipeline in shadow mode, producing alerts that nobody sees, with a clinical-quality team reviewing every alert and rating it on a useful-or-not scale. The shadow data is the gold for the relevance layer and it is borderline impossible to collect after the system is live and clinicians are reacting to alerts. Most teams realize this in month two of live operation when they are trying to explain why the rapid response team has stopped responding to pages from the system.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    626[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    627[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The artifact problem deserves more respect than it usually gets. Bedside monitor artifact rates are 5% to 30% depending on the population, and the difficult cases are not the obvious lead-off artifacts (those are easy to filter). The hard ones are subtle: a SpO2 finger probe that has partially slipped and is reading 89% instead of 95% for half an hour, a blood pressure cuff that did not inflate properly and recorded a low systolic, an ECG that is picking up motion artifact during patient ambulation. Each of those will trigger your trajectory detector and each requires a different set of signals to suppress. The first version of every monitoring pipeline I have built spent more engineering effort on artifact than on trajectory math, which felt wrong at the time and turned out to be exactly right.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    628[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    629[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing I underestimated, repeatedly, is the routing. Where exactly does the alert go? The rapid response team's pager? The charge nurse's phone? The bedside monitor's escalation indicator? The EHR's deterioration column? All of the above with deduplication? Different units want different routing. Different shifts want different routing. The on-call attending wants different routing than the day-shift hospitalist. Each routing decision is a conversation with the unit leadership, and each conversation has a different answer. The right architecture treats routing as a configuration table, not a code path, and exposes the configuration to the clinical-quality team.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    630[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    631[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Finally: the explanation matters as much as the detection. A surfaced alert that says "high deterioration risk" is too thin for a sleep-deprived nurse at 03:00 to act on. A surfaced alert that says "NEWS2 has risen from 2 to 8 over the last hour, driven primarily by respiratory rate up to 26 from baseline 17 and oxygen saturation down to 91% from baseline 96%, pattern consistent with developing infection or respiratory compromise, recommend bedside evaluation and consider sepsis workup" is something the nurse can act on. The narrative is the product. The math just produces the inputs to the narrative.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    632[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    633[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    634[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    635[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Variations and Extensions
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    636[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    637[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-modal early warning with lab and assessment integration.** The vital-sign-only pipeline described here is a strong foundation, but the richest deterioration models combine trajectories of vitals with lab values (lactate, white blood cell count, BUN, creatinine), clinical assessments (Glasgow Coma Scale changes, pain scores, nursing concern flags), and recent intervention history. Recipe 3.7 (Patient Deterioration Early Warning) covers the multi-modal version. A common evolution path is to start with vitals-only and layer in additional signals over the first year of operation as the team builds confidence in the foundation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    638[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    639[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Patient-specific score calibration.** A patient with chronic obstructive pulmonary disease has a baseline oxygen saturation of 88% to 92% at home; for them, an SpO2 of 90% is normal, not deterioration. Standard NEWS2 incorrectly scores this as 1 to 3 points. A more sophisticated layer adjusts the per-component thresholds based on patient-specific history when available, computing a "personal NEWS2" that respects the patient's chronic state. This requires clinical workflow buy-in (the personalized score must be visible to the staff alongside the standard score) and careful management of the override semantics (the system should always be able to trip on absolute thresholds regardless of personalization).
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    640[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    641[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Wearable and remote-monitoring integration.** The same trajectory pipeline architecture extends from in-hospital monitoring to post-discharge remote monitoring with continuous vitals from wearables (continuous SpO2 patches, ambulatory ECG, smartwatch-derived metrics). The pipeline is the same; the artifact characteristics, the patient-specific baselines, and the alert delivery surface are different (push notifications to the patient and their care team rather than pager to the RRT). Recipe 7.x (Remote Patient Monitoring) covers the variation.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    642[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    643[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Shadow-mode operation for tuning.** Run the entire pipeline in shadow mode for the first two to three months before go-live. Surface the alerts to a quality-review queue rather than to clinical staff. Have a clinical-quality team (an attending physician, a senior nurse, a clinical analyst) review every alert and rate it on usefulness. Use the ratings to tune the relevance layer. The shadow data is operationally invaluable and is borderline impossible to collect post-launch.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    644[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    645[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Federated learning across hospitals.** A health system with multiple hospitals can train the joint deterioration model federated across them without centralizing the patient-level data. Each hospital trains locally; only model gradients flow to a central aggregator. This is particularly attractive for academic-community partnerships where the academic site has data depth and the community sites have volume. The architecture adds complexity but addresses the data-governance friction that often blocks cross-hospital model training.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    646[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    647[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Integration with rapid response team workflow.** Move beyond pager-based alerting to fuller workflow integration: the alert opens an RRT case in the EHR with the relevant context pre-populated, the case includes the bedside vital sign trajectory chart, the disposition decision (RRT activated, escalation deferred, false alarm) is captured back as feedback. This closes the loop and is the strongest path to continuous improvement of the relevance rules.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    648[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    649[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    650[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    651[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Related Recipes
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    652[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    653[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 3.7 (Patient Deterioration Early Warning):** The multi-modal version of this recipe that combines vital sign trajectories with lab trends, clinical assessments, and intervention history. Builds directly on the streaming pipeline described here.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    654[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 12.4 (Lab Result Trend Analysis):** The chronic-context counterpart to this recipe focused on slow lab trajectories in ambulatory settings. Shares the baseline computation and clinical relevance patterns; differs in cadence, signal characteristics, and clinical workflow.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    655[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 12.5 (Hospital Census Forecasting):** The operational counterpart that forecasts inpatient census and downstream impact. A trajectory monitoring system that escalates a patient to ICU couples to the census forecast.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    656[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 12.10 (Physiological Waveform Analysis):** The high-frequency-waveform version of this problem (ECG arrhythmia detection, seizure prediction from EEG). Different statistical machinery; complementary clinical use case.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    657[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 3.5 (Lab Result Outlier Detection):** Single-value outlier detection that complements trajectory detection. Outliers catch the dramatic single-value spikes; trajectories catch the slow accumulating drift.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    658[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Recipe 11.7 (Chronic Disease Management Coach):** The patient-facing remote-monitoring counterpart that surfaces wearable-derived trajectories to the patient and their care team rather than to a hospital RRT.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    659[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    660[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
